The rain in Oakhaven didn't wash things clean; it just made the pavement slicker, turning the cobblestones into a mosaic of silver and black. For Leo, the school was a place where the rules were written in stone and the teachers wore robes of velvet, but the reality was a chaotic, neon-lit jungle of secrets.

Leo was a sophomore in History, the kind of student who loved the dusty archives and the smell of old parchment. But his heart was a small, dark forest, and he had been hiding it since he was seven.

His name was Elias, but to the world, he was just Leo.

The first day of school, Leo walked through the hallway with a heavy heart. He saw the teacher, Mrs. Gable, polishing her spectacles. She was a woman of sharp lines and a voice that could cut through a storm. Leo felt a chill run down his spine, not from the cold rain, but from the weight of the truth.

"Leo," Mrs. Gable said, her voice smooth and practiced. "You're late. The library is closed for the annual reading."

Leo didn't answer. He knew the library was closed. He knew the reading was a lie. He knew that if he told the truth, he would be caught. If he lied, he would be a fraud.

He walked to the back of the school, past the cafeteria where the students were eating their lunch in a sea of plastic wrappers and cardboard boxes. He stopped at the school gate, where the school bus was waiting. The driver, a tall man named Marcus, looked up from his phone.

"Leo?" Marcus asked, his voice a low rumble. "You're late again. The bus is full."

Leo didn't look at him. He looked at the bus, then at the empty seats in the back. He thought of the library, the dusty stacks, the smell of ink. He thought of the forest, the roots, the silence.

He didn't say anything. He just waited.

The bus pulled up. The driver, Marcus, stepped out. He looked at Leo, then at the empty seats. He saw the dark shape in the corner of the window.

"Leo?" Marcus repeated, his voice trembling slightly. "You're late. The bus is full."

Leo didn't look at him. He looked at the bus, then at the empty seats. He thought of the library, the dusty stacks, the smell of ink. He thought of the forest, the roots, the silence.

He didn't say anything. He just waited.

